cs.LG, cs.AI, cs.CV, cs.NE, cs.SI 

The paper proposes a novel discriminative approach to disease progression modeling using biomarkers, which involves estimating the sequence in which biomarkers become abnormal. This is a machine learning problem that involves ranking and ordering, which suggests that the paper could belong to several sub-categories. 

cs.LG (Machine Learning) is the most likely sub-category as the paper proposes a new machine learning model for disease progression modeling. 

cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) is also likely as the paper involves using machine learning to understand the dynamics of disease progression and facilitate early diagnosis. 

cs.CV (Computer Vision) is a possibility as the paper mentions using neuroimaging data from the Alzheimer's Disease Neuroimaging Initiative (ADNI) to estimate the central event ordering in the dataset. 

cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing) is another possibility as the paper involves modeling the progression of Alzheimer's disease using biomarkers, which could involve neural networks or evolutionary algorithms. 

cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) is a less likely possibility, but the paper does involve estimating a central ordering over all subjects based on subject-specific orderings, which could be seen as a network problem.
